page.text: In 2006, the City of Olympia and the Washington State Department of Transportation (WSDOT)
partnered on the West Olympia Access Study to determine what transportation system
changes were needed to preserve future mobility. The West Olympia Access Study (WOAS) was
initiated with the purpose of evaluating current and future multi-modal mobility concerns on
Olympia’s west side, and identifying a strategy for improving access and circulation. The
partnership recognized that both agencies have a vested interest in addressing mobility
The core study team included staff representatives from the City of Olympia, WSDOT Olympic
Region, WSDOT Headquarters, and Thurston Regional Planning Council (TRPC) and the project
consultant. This core team worked closely with representatives from the WSDOT Headquarters
and the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA) to obtain conceptual approval of access
improvements to US 101 based on an alternatives evaluation and preliminary Interchange
In 2010, the outcome of this process directed City of Olympia staff to advance work into the
next phase of implementation including an IJR, environmental documentation, and supporting
design work to achieve formal approval to build new ramps to and from US-101. An outcome
of the previous study also identified a “phased” implementation strategy to construct the

The purpose of the US 101 West Olympia Access Project is to evaluate current and future
mobility concerns on Olympia’s west side and to identify a range of measures to address
mobility and improve access and circulation.
This study was identified in the WSDOT 2003-2022 Highway System Plan (HSP), as well as in
the current HSP (2007-2026) as a ‘solution that requires further analyses’. In addition, the City
of Olympia Comprehensive Plan identifies the need for additional access to West Olympia from
There is growing concern within the community about congestion and the lack of travel routing
choices on both local and state networks. Additionally, the environment for traveling by transit,
bicycling, and walking does not encourage these travel modes. Increasing congestion raises
questions about the best ways to accommodate growth, while maintaining safe and acceptable
levels of mobility for all travel modes.
The existing transportation network in the West Olympia study area includes the interchanges
of US 101 with Black Lake Boulevard and Crosby Boulevard/Cooper Point Road. It also includes
the Cooper Point Road/Black Lake Boulevard intersection. These critical junctions in the West

page.text: Olympia street network are inadequate to meet growing travel demand based on future traffic
forecasts. Of particular concern is the Black Lake Boulevard/Cooper Point Road intersection
where delay often impacts vehicle trips, including emergency responders who must access the
Capital Medical Center. The 2025 Regional Transportation Plan (RTP) indicates that even with
efficiency measures, the Cooper Point Road/Black Lake Boulevard intersection will fail within
the next 20 years. This would cause undesirable delays and would also adversely impact traffic
operations on nearby roads and intersections, including US 101 interchanges.
The Interchange Justification Report (IJR) for US 101 will encompass the area between its
interchanges with I-5 and Evergreen Parkway and will include preparation of:
Conceptual and preliminary design of the new interchanges at Kaiser Road and Yauger
This project will address the current conditions, future needs, and environmental impacts
associated with enhancing traffic operations, safety, and efficiency along the US 101 mainline
in the vicinity of the US 101/Black Lake Boulevard Interchange.
As sponsors of the project, the following individual groups will set the goals and requirements
for the project and its deliverables.
Depending on the degree of impacts associated with the planned improvement, it is
envisioned that project environmental documentation will be either an Environmental
Classification Summary (ECS) or an Environmental Assessment (EA).
The proposed improvements will include revisions to existing interchange configurations. As
required by WSDOT and FHWA, eight specific policy points will be addressed in the IJR. The
technical content of the eight point discussion is presented below. During earlier phases of the
West Olympia Access study, several of these points were thoroughly evaluated including Policy
Points #1, #2 and #3, leading to initial identification of recommended improvements. In the
current study effort, this analysis will be updated and documented in policy point format.

page.text: For freeway operations, the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual (HCM) using the associated
Highway Capacity software (HCS) (version 6.5) will be used to analyze mainline, merge/diverge
connections and weaving segments. Average vehicle speed and density will be used as
performance measures for the HCS analysis. For the three analysis years (2014, 2020 and
2040), AM and PM peak hour analyses will be performed.
For ramp terminal/surface street operations, intersections will be analyzed as follows:
Synchro 8.0 software will be used to analyze the operations of signalized intersections.

SimTraffic software will be used to check Synchro results for ramp queuing
For the proposed alternative, a simulation model capable of analyzing freeway and geometry
between intersections, including weaving sections and multiple vehicle classes will be used.
The prior study created a simulation and operational model using VISSIM software and this
model will be updated to reflect changes in the travel forecasts. As the PM peak hour currently
experiences higher levels of congestion than the AM peak, only PM peak hour analysis will be
conducted using this tool. The following VISSIM simulations will be prepared:

The existing TRPC Emme/3 travel demand model will be utilized to develop forecasts for 2020
(year of opening) and 2040 (design year). The 2020 forecast will include all local and regional
improvements for which funding is committed and that are expected to be in place by 2020.
The 2040 model will include projects adopted in the region’s Regional Transportation Plan
(RTP). Travel forecasts for the AM and PM peak hours will be prepared.

page.text: The existing TRPC model was selected as the preferred model to support evaluation of US 101
mainline and interchange concepts in the study area. The model study area includes all of
Thurston County, including major highways and a finely detailed network of local streets. The
base year of this model is 2009 and the planning horizon year is 2035. An update to 2040 is
currently under development but will not be available until 2015. No interim year (i.e., 2020)
Traffic forecasts for 2040 will be developed by calculating the traffic growth between 2009 and
2035 and extending the annualized growth rate by five more years. Traffic forecasts for 2020
will be developed by interpolating output between the 2009 and 2035 models.
The effect of network changes will be isolated from land-use changes on the future traffic
forecasts so that only growth associated with land-use changes will be extrapolated or
Testing of future scenarios will be conducted to review model sensitivity to changes in travel
demand or the model network using the new TRPC model when it is available in 2015.
Future interchange and intersection traffic volumes will be developed using travel forecasts
from the model. The model travel forecasts for each time period will be post-processed and
translated into vehicle volumes for use in the operations analysis. The interchange and
intersection volumes will be balanced using the freeway ramp volumes as control totals.
The following baseline conditions are assumed:
o Funded TIP improvements from local jurisdictions
o RTP transportation improvements from local and state jurisdictions.
Improvements from the Regional Transportation Plan will be reviewed by the IJR Support
Group and selected improvements will be included.

This corridor-specific information as well as statewide system collision statistics will be used in

Options for improving access to US 101 without degrading the mainline freeway or on/off-
ramp operations and safety will be analyzed and reviewed in this IJR, environmental
documentation, and preliminary design effort. While degradation of the state highway system
is not an acceptable outcome, there may be localized areas where degradation may occur due
to system tradeoffs. Engineering judgment will be applied to arrive at the best overall set of
practical improvements within the study area. Project stakeholders will be asked to approve all
